": "respiratory distress", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9329571723937988, "span": {"begin": 1898, "end": 1918}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:56603"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP26B1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9943342208862305, "span": {"begin": 1982, "end": 1989}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:56603"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP26B1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9759066700935364, "span": {"begin": 2022, "end": 2029}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9930458664894104, "span": {"begin": 2081, "end": 2086}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9937729835510254, "span": {"begin": 2227, "end": 2232}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:56603"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP26B1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9610748291015625, "span": {"begin": 2285, "end": 2292}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:56603"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP26B1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9724724888801575, "span": {"begin": 2339, "end": 2346}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "all-trans RA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9983189105987549, "span": {"begin": 2364, "end": 2376}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:56603"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP26B1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9685256481170654, "span": {"begin": 2426, "end": 2433}}, {"id": ["mesh:C496908"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "4-OH-RA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9989938735961914, "span": {"begin": 2443, "end": 2450}}, {"id": ["mesh:C013570"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "18-OH-RA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9982614517211914, "span": {"begin": 2455, "end": 2463}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:56603"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP26B1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9658825397491455, "span": {"begin": 2490, "end": 2497}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "all-trans-RA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987923502922058, "span": {"begin": 2545, "end": 2557}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:50648"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "9-cis-RA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9981063604354858, "span": {"begin": 2563, "end": 2571}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:6067"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "13-cis-", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9950700402259827, "span": {"begin": 2577, "end": 2584}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:56603"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP26B1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9358204007148743, "span": {"begin": 2629, "end": 2636}}], "text": "CYP26B1 and its function  Numerous physiological processes as well as fetal development is dependent on correct levels of retinoic acid (RA). RA homeostasis is tightly regulated and involves, amongst many other factors, breakdown by the Cytochrome P450 enzymes of family 26 (Kedishvili, 2013; White et al, 1997; White et al, 1996). The family consists of the enzymes CYP26A1, CYP26B1, and CYP26C1 (Isoherranen &amp; Zhong, 2019). These RA-metabolizing enzymes convert all-trans-RA to more polar metabolites, including 4-hydroxy-RA and 4-oxo-RA (White et al, 1996; White et al, 2000).  CYP26B1 is particularly important for the clearance of RA in the fetal mouse testis, with knockout models having established its critical role in normal testis development in preventing premature meiotic initiation of male germ cells (Bowles et al, 2018; Bowles et al, 2006; Li et al, 2009; MacLean et al, 2007). CYP26B1 is necessary for steroidogenesis and male reproductive tract formation (Bowles et al, 2018), and may also play a role in maintaining normal spermatogenesis in the adult male mouse (Hogarth et al, 2015). CYP26B1 has been shown to be expressed in the postnatal mouse ovary, where it is proposed to regulate granulosa cell proliferation (Kipp et al, 2011).   In addition to reproductive development, CYP26B1 is important for other aspects of embryonic development. The expression of CYP26B1 is initiated at embryonic day 8 in the mouse hindbrain and is expressed in the limb buds from the beginning of their outgrowth as well as later in many different tissues during organ development including the genital tubercle, craniofacial areas, and spinal cord (Abu-Abed et al, 2002; MacLean et al, 2001; Ross &amp; Zolfaghari, 2011). Consistent with this, Cyp26b1-knockout mice display various developmental defects including severe limb malformations and pups born alive die right after birth due to respiratory distress (Yashiro et al, 2004).&nbsp;   Besides from the important role CYP26B1 plays during fetal development, CYP26B1 is also expressed in multiple tissues in the adult human including adipose tissue, bladder, blood vessels, brain, kidney, adrenals, liver, lung, pancreas, intestines, testis, uterus, and skin (The-Human-Protein-Atlas, 2021; Topletz et al, 2012).  &nbsp;  CYP26B1 inhibition as Key Event  The main function of CYP26B1 is to inactivate all-trans RA. The major primary metabolites formed from RA by CYP26B1 are&nbsp;4-OH-RA and 18-OH-RA (Topletz et al, 2012) and CYP26B1 shows preference for the following substrates: all-trans-RA &gt; 9-cis-RA &gt; 13-cis-RA (Topletz et al, 2012; White et al, 2000). CYP26B1 is regulated by a range of molecular factors but also by RA itself (Isoherranen &amp; Zhong, 2019; White et al, 2000).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:52:57 +0000 2026"}